{"id":"1003.0415","submitter":"Joel Tropp","authors":"Joel A. Tropp","title":"The Sparsity Gap: Uncertainty Principles Proportional to Dimension","comments":"6 pages. To appear in the Proceedings of the 44th Ann. IEEE Conf. on\n  Information Sciences and Systems","journal-ref":"Invited paper, Proc. 44th IEEE Conf. Information Sciences and\n  Systems (CISS), pp. 1-6, Princeton, NJ, Mar. 2010","doi":"10.1109/CISS.2010.5464824","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In an incoherent dictionary, most signals that admit a sparse representation\nadmit a unique sparse representation. In other words, there is no way to\nexpress the signal without using strictly more atoms. This work demonstrates\nthat sparse signals typically enjoy a higher privilege: each nonoptimal\nrepresentation of the signal requires far more atoms than the sparsest\nrepresentation-unless it contains many of the same atoms as the sparsest\nrepresentation. One impact of this finding is to confer a certain degree of\nlegitimacy on the particular atoms that appear in a sparse representation. This\nresult can also be viewed as an uncertainty principle for random sparse signals\nover an incoherent dictionary.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Mar 2010 18:28:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-18"}
